            <p>
              Hello! I have no idea how you ended up here, but otherwise, I will
              apologize for what seems like either a run of bad luck for you or
              maybe your just having a bad day. Either way, I am glad your here.
              My name is
              <b>Phillip Jackson</b>,
              <i>a.k.a</i>
              <b>Unisys12</b>. Online, most of my friends call me Uni.
            </p>
          </section>
          <section>
            <p>
              In February of 2020, my wife started her own business as a dog
              trainer. In November of 2020, she was scheduled to have surgery
              which was going to require a 3 to 4-week recovery time. We had
              planned for this, my employer included, by me saving all my
              vacation time for this period. At around the same time is when
              COVID-19 started having a greater impact locally. I ended up being
              off work for 2 months straight. During this period, my wife and I
              discussed me leaving my then current job and coming home to help
              her. She had tried hiring several different people so they could
              assist her and was unable to find someone with a drive and passion
              for animals, coupled with a sense of responsibility. For various
              reasons, I was looking for a change. Not so much in my carrier,
              per-say. But simply a chance to do something more. After 16 years
              at Rayco, Inc, I felt like I had nowhere else to go or anything
              else to offer. And learning how to train dogs was going to be a
              whole new world that I was free to explore. Since I was going to
              be self-employed, the only ladder I had to climb was the one I
              propped up for myself. If I wanted to go higher, at any time, I
              could. And I did! I have enjoyed this time tremendously and do not
              regret my decision to leave my old job in the slightest. During
              these last few years, I have grown so much and even at 50 years of
              age I feel as though I have matured. Slightly. I have a new-found
              respect for business owners and the mental capacity needed to
              maintain that business. I have never worked harder in my life than
              I have since leaving my old job.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section>
